# worktree-parallel-agent-execution — History

## v1.5.0 (2026-05-18)

**Changed by:** ProjectAgamemnon F-phase remediation dispatch (PRs #407, #409, #410) — 3 parallel Sonnet `general-purpose` impl agents told "no worktree, work in main workdir"
**Verification:** verified-ci

### What changed

- Added new subsection "No-worktree-at-all anti-pattern (v1.5.0) — same workdir, N agents, HEAD-flip contamination" inside "Verified Workflow"
- Documents the failure mode where parallel impl agents are explicitly told to skip worktrees because their files are disjoint, and the resulting silent HEAD-flip + commit-leak between branches
- Added verified workflow: explicit `git worktree add /tmp/<project>-<phase>` per-agent in the dispatch prompt
- Added decision matrix for workdir strategy by agent type (Sonnet impl vs Haiku fix-agent vs cross-reference needs vs EASY-tier swarm)
- Added recovery workflow using `git reflog` when contamination has happened mid-flight
- Added 2 new Failed Attempts rows: "3 parallel Sonnet impl agents with 'no worktree'" and "Harness `isolation: \"worktree\"` flag for cross-reference agents"
- Added 1 new Verified On row for ProjectAgamemnon F-phase (2026-05-18)
- Extended frontmatter `description` with trigger (11) covering the no-worktree-at-all anti-pattern
- Cross-referenced sibling skill `feedback-swarm-branch-collision` as the REMOTE-race companion to this LOCAL same-workdir variant
- Updated Overview date to 2026-05-18 and Outcome line to mention v1.5.0 foundation PRs
- Bumped version to 1.5.0 (minor — new section + new failure mode + 2 failed-attempt rows; no breaking changes)

### Why

The existing skill covered three contamination variants: (a) `isolation: "worktree"` index/HEAD
contention across distinct branches (Phase 0a, v1.2.0), (b) remote branch-namespace collapse onto
one ref (v1.3.0), (c) partial stray-commit leak (v1.4.0). All three assume agents ARE using some
form of worktree isolation. The new failure mode is a step earlier in the decision tree: the
orchestrator deliberately told agents to skip worktrees entirely because their files were disjoint.
This produces a strictly worse failure than worktree-based contamination — silent HEAD-flipping in
the shared workdir requires `git reflog` archaeology to recover, where worktree-based contamination
at least leaves clean branch boundaries. Verified on ProjectAgamemnon F-phase 2026-05-18 across
PRs #407, #409, #410: all three merged after each agent independently discovered the contamination
(~15min/agent wasted wall-clock). The lesson: parallel Sonnet dispatch ≠ parallel-safe filesystem
access. Make explicit `git worktree add` a HARD RULE in the prompt template, not a suggestion.

